d 4.2.4.Final."},"partialFingerprints": {"vulnerabilityHash": "0c969a150662145d981882b3fe54de13"},"locations": [{"physicalLocation": {"artifactLocation": {"uri": "file://\/home\/webemo-aaron\/.gradle\/caches\/modules-2\/files-2.1\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll\/4.1.122.Final\/236a1f77a06b1264fe61fca3183a09e9161378c8\/netty-transport-native-epoll-4.1.122.Final-linux-x86_64.jar","index": 513 }},"logicalLocations": [{"fullyQualifiedName": "pkg:maven\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll@4.1.122.Final"}]}]}, {"ruleId": "CVE-2025-58057","level": "warning","message": {"text": "CVE-2025-58057 - Netty is an asynchronous event-driven network application framework for rapid development of maintainable high performance protocol servers & clients. In netty-codec-compression versions 4.1.124.Final and below, and netty-codec versions 4.2.4.Final and below, when supplied with specially crafted input, BrotliDecoder and certain other decompression decoders will allocate a large number of reachable byte buffers, which can lead to denial of service. BrotliDecoder.decompress has no limit in how often it calls pull, decompressing data 64K bytes at a time. The buffers are saved in the output list, and remain reachable until OOM is hit. This is fixed in versions 4.1.125.Final of netty-codec and 4.2.5.Final of netty-codec-compression."},"partialFingerprints": {"vulnerabilityHash": "3fe2aa0a7788128435dfcac6ffb56be7"},"locations": [{"physicalLocation": {"artifactLocation": {"uri": "file://\/home\/webemo-aaron\/.gradle\/caches\/modules-2\/files-2.1\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll\/4.1.122.Final\/236a1f77a06b1264fe61fca3183a09e9161378c8\/netty-transport-native-epoll-4.1.122.Final-linux-x86_64.jar","index": 513 }},"logicalLocations": [{"fullyQualifiedName": "pkg:maven\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll@4.1.122.Final"}]}]}, {"ruleId": "CVE-2025-67735","level": "warning","message": {"text": "CVE-2025-67735 - Netty is an asynchronous, event-driven network application framework. In versions prior to 4.1.129.Final and 4.2.8.Final, the `io.netty.handler.codec.http.HttpRequestEncoder` has a CRLF injection with the request URI when constructing a request. This leads to request smuggling when `HttpRequestEncoder` is used without proper sanitization of the URI. Any application \/ framework using `HttpRequestEncoder` can be subject to be abused to perform request smuggling using CRLF injection. Versions 4.1.129.Final and 4.2.8.Final fix the issue."},"partialFingerprints": {"vulnerabilityHash": "3094b2cfe65f6d785516687d86432ffe"},"locations": [{"physicalLocation": {"artifactLocation": {"uri": "file://\/home\/webemo-aaron\/.gradle\/caches\/modules-2\/files-2.1\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll\/4.1.122.Final\/236a1f77a06b1264fe61fca3183a09e9161378c8\/netty-transport-native-epoll-4.1.122.Final-linux-x86_64.jar","index": 513 }},"logicalLocations": [{"fullyQualifiedName": "pkg:maven\/io.netty\/netty-transport-native-epoll@4.1.122.Final"}]}]}, {"ruleId": "CVE-2025-58056","level": "warning","message": {"text": "CVE-2025-58056 - Netty is an asynchronous event-driven network application framework for development of maintainable high performance protocol servers and clients. In versions 4.1.124.Final, and 4.2.0.Alpha3 through 4.2.4.Final, Netty incorrectly accepts standalone newline characters (LF) as a chunk-size line terminator, regardless of a preceding carriage return (CR), instead of requiring CRLF per HTTP\/1.1 standards. When combined with reverse proxies that parse LF differently (treating it as part of the chunk extension), attackers can craft requests that the proxy sees as one request but Netty processes as two, enabling request smuggling attacks. This is fixed in versions 4.1.125.Final and 4.2.5.Final."},"partialFingerprints": {"vulnerabilityHash": "a738a02bd1c5332d3324e5f11dd5df58"},"locations": [{"physicalLocation": {"artifactLocation": {"uri": "file://\/home\/webemo-aaron\/.gradle\/caches\/modules-2\/files-2.1\/io.netty\/netty-tran